{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/child-maltreatment-recognition-management/background-information/risk-factors/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"39584d8d-795e-5390-bca9-43362ddf7157","slug":"risk-factors","fullItemName":"Risk factors","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field f55a80d4-155c-44b1-a083-151df2e742f9 --><h2>What are the risk factors?</h2><!-- end field f55a80d4-155c-44b1-a083-151df2e742f9 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item fe2a3bc0-743a-49f6-9398-f64c83b16b0c --><!-- begin field 2c9329fc-585d-4ed7-a6b3-519c4601a9ea --><ul><li><strong>Risk factors for child maltreatment include:</strong><ul><li><strong>Family and environmental risk factors:</strong><ul><li>Poverty and financial pressures, poor housing — may be associated with a higher level of parental stress and an increased risk of child maltreatment.</li><li>Maltreatment of other children within the family, intrafamilial violence.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Parental risk factors (which may be compounded by lack of support from family or friends):</strong><ul><li>Substance misuse.</li><li>A history of domestic abuse, including sexual violence or exploitation, and/or maltreatment as a child.</li><li>Emotional volatility or having problems managing anger.</li><li>A history of violent offending.</li><li>Mental health problems which have a significant impact on the tasks of parenting.</li><li>Known maltreatment of animals.</li><li>Poor education.</li><li>Lack of parenting knowledge.</li><li>Learning difficulties. Child maltreatment may occur due to a lack of understanding of parental responsibilities and limited support.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Child risk factors:</strong><ul><li>Physical and/or mental impairment. This may be due to factors including impaired capacity to resist or avoid maltreatment, lack of effective communication and inability to understand what is happening or to seek help, and dependency on carers for personal assistance. </li><li>Living in the care system. </li><li>Being a twin or multiple.</li></ul></li></ul></li><li><strong>Risk factors for recurring or persistent child abuse and neglect include:</strong><ul><li>Refusal by the parent or carer to engage with services.</li><li>The parent or carer experiencing a mental health or substance misuse problem which has a significant impact on the tasks of parenting.</li><li>Chronic parental stress.</li><li>The parent or carer experienced abuse or neglect as a child.</li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/child-maltreatment-recognition-management/references/\">HM Government, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/child-maltreatment-recognition-management/references/\">NICE, 2017b</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/child-maltreatment-recognition-management/references/\">NICE, 2017a</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/child-maltreatment-recognition-management/references/\">BMJ Best Practice, 2018</a>]</p><!-- end field 2c9329fc-585d-4ed7-a6b3-519c4601a9ea --><!-- end item fe2a3bc0-743a-49f6-9398-f64c83b16b0c -->","topic":{"id":"399c706c-d925-5357-8bd0-fb82cd95ee01","topicId":"7e199db4-11c4-42e5-8f2d-878014e6b1ee","topicName":"Child maltreatment - recognition and management","slug":"child-maltreatment-recognition-management","lastRevised":"Last revised in January 2019","chapters":[{"id":"44455b04-f8f9-5618-936e-0f3ee64eff15","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"adf16a06-53ba-50f6-b77c-723ecd9b3220","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"d5b2b953-c8cc-5be0-b514-38c4c95eca62","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"727476e5-0ff0-56a5-a9b2-7dc9ce1c5de4","slug":"changes","fullItemNa